Tanzania plans to spend a total of 2bn/- to construct and renovate 63 police stations initially built by the public as part of efforts to curb criminal activities in their areas. Deputy Minister of State in the President’s Office, Regional Administration and Local Government (PO-RALG), Dr Festo Dugange told parliamentarians in Dodoma on Friday detailing that so far  1.85bn/- (about 85 percent) has been released as of December 2021. Responding to a question from Daud Venant, (Igalula -CCM) who sought to know the government’s strategy in completing various structures that have been built by the citizens for Education, Health and Police purposes. Equally the minister said the government has set aside a total of 43.8bn/- in the 2021/2022 financial year for the completion of dispensaries and Health centers. He said over 29.5bn/- has already been released for the project. Mr Dugange added that a sum of 79bn/- has also been disbursed for the completion of classrooms and laboratories. “The government is aware of the 1,715 fortified dispensaries and health centers that were established by citizen’s efforts which require a total of 98.7bn/- for its completion also in the education sector there is a total of 12,101 structures that require 183.5bn/- to be completed,” the Minister said.